description.plain:
Justine Skye (born August 24, 1995) was born in  Fort Greene, Brooklyn, New York. Skye started gaining fame from Tumblr, which she gained a music career and was signed to Atlantic Records at 19 years old.

She tagged along with her mother, an entertainment lawyer, to a music panel held by performance rights organization BMI. During the question-and-answer session, Justine surprised everyone in attendance by asking to sing. In front of various music executives, she performed a cover of Sam Sparro’s “Black and Gold.” The Brooklyn native subsequently took singing lessons and honed her songwriting, then worked with August Rigo (Justin Bieber, One Direction, Musiq Soulchild) and Eric Hudson (Kanye West, Diddy, August Alsina). Their sessions led to Everyday Living, a confident contemporary R&B EP released on Atlantic in August 2013. The brief collection featured a cover of Aaliyah’s “I Don’t Wanna.” In August 2014, Justine returned with the slow-jam single “Collide,” a DJ Mustard production that involved a guest verse from Tyga. (via iTunes)

description.plain:
In “Know Myself,“ Justine and Vory take turns to sing on matters of love from their respective points of view.  Driven by a slow-tempo afrobeat paired with mellow bass pickings and simple key melodies, they detail the unfairness of their lovers remarking that they know one another better than they know themselves.

Notably, this song was released eight months before Justine’s critically acclaimed single “Build,” which gave insight into the pain of suffering from domestic abuse in a relationship. Therefore, it can be assumed this song was written during the time Justine was in that same toxic relationship. In an October 2018 interview with Billboard, Justine expanded on the difficulties faced within the relationship and creating music that draws from these personal situations:


People will hurt you in a relationship, but for the most part, [I feel] you may love this person so much that you do not want to believe it. So, [perhaps] you choose to ignore all of the signs, even when they are directly in your face.

When I am a part of the process, you can tell. You can tell when [a record] is authentic or when it is just a song that anyone can sing.

description.plain:
This song is about Justine Skye coming in and stealing the show from who is out there now.

You wanna go play right away, well I’m fine with that
We some and drink all day, baby, and I’m faded like
I can’t remember your name, right away, what I’m tryna say
I got that game changed, I got that game changed

This whole section is about the people in the industry that shes hanging around now that aren’t taking her seriously and she knows. And that one soon people will forget about them and know who she is because shes going to change whats going on.

The proverbial “secret” Is that shes about to take over. “say nothing that you know youre gonna regret” is someone saying or thinking she cant because shell prove them wrong.

“Ooh yeah, you’ve been looking for the wrong one baby
Ooh yeah, and I know what to do to make you go crazy”

This all means people have been paying attention to the wrong people and now that Justines here shes going to play and do things they make people want her.

Over the sleek and airy production, Skye comes to her senses and realizes things weren’t exactly how they seemed.

description.plain:
“X2C” is an unreleased collaboration between Justine Skye and Travis Scott. The track appears unfinished, featuring Justine’s vocals looping throughout, and Travis mumble as he attempts to lay down some rough ideas and test flows, as is common with many demos.

In the song, Justine tells the story of someone who swiftly moved on from a past relationship with her in an attempt to make their ex jealous. Its title is a play on ‘XTCY,’ an abbreviation for the party drug ecstasy; the hook also utilises this play on words.

Thought to have been recorded in 2015, the song remained unreleased and unheard of until a snippet of it leaked online on November 13, 2019, with a second following on January 15, 2020. The full track surfaced on February 24, 2020.

description.plain:
Released on April 20th, 2015, “A Train” finds Skye paying homage to the famed New York City subway system. Over the gritty Kadis and Sean-produced beat, the Atlantic Records signee delivers a soothing message – one person’s daily commute is another person’s getaway.



Interestingly enough, the artwork does not feature an image of the A train. Instead it captures the Flushing-bound 7 stopped at the 33rd Street – Rawson Street station. In this comparison photo you can see both the Empire State Building and One Court Square in the background – both are visible in the song’s artwork.
